--- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;javayoffe&quot; &lt;javayoffe@y...&gt; wrote:
&gt; I want to execute my unit tests with both logging set to DEBUG and 
&gt; then execute them again with logging set to FATAL.   This is to 
&gt; ensure that no bugs exist/are introduced that will be exhibited only 
&gt; when logging is set to a certain level.   An example of such a bug 
&gt; might be:

Here&#39;s another one (which has bitten me before): classes that, during
initialisation, have an invalid hashcode, which are populated via the
Apache Commons BeanUtils - at a low enough log level, it tries to
print the hashcode, causing NullPointerExceptions.

&gt; Either way, is there something more clever that I can do to 
&gt; accomplish my goal of testing min/max logging levels?

Try this: create your test class as normal, then give it a suite()
method that does this:

public static Test suite() {
  TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
  suite.add(LoggingTestSetup.decorate(ThisTest.class, Level.DEBUG));
  suite.add(LoggingTestSetup.decorate(ThisTest.class, Level.FATAL));
}


LoggingTestSetup looks like this:

import junit.extensions.TestSetup;
public class LoggingTestSetup extends TestSetup {
  private Level logLevel;
  private Level oldLogLevel;

  private LoggingTestSetup(Test test, Level level) {
    super(test);
    logLevel = level;
  }

  protected void setUp() {
    oldLogLevel = ...; // lookup the current log level.
    // set the log level
  }

  protected void tearDown() {
    // reset the log level.
  }

  public static Test decorate(Class&lt;? extends TestCase&gt; test, Level
level) {
    return new LoggingTestSetup(new TestSuite(test), level);
  }
}


You&#39;ll get two passes over the code base - once with the DEBUG level,
and again with the FATAL level.
